record_data.record_plain_text: TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT between Prairie Rose Transmission, LLC and Prairie Rose Wind, LLC Dated as of August 2, 2012 Prairie Rose Wind Farm Interconnection Facilities TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT THIS TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is entered into as of August 2, 2012 (the “Execution Date”), by and between PRAIRIE ROSE WIND, LLC, a New York limited liability company (“Prairie Rose”), and PRAIRIE ROSE TRANSMISSION, LLC, a Minnesota limited liability company (“PR Transmission”) (each a “Party,” and collectively referred to as, the “Parties”). RECITALS A. Prairie Rose is developing, and will construct, own and operate, a two hundred megawatt (200 MW) wind-powered electric generation facility located in Rocky County, Minnesota (the “Wind Farm”). B. The Wind Farm will connect to the Project Substation defined below to be constructed, owned and operated by PR Transmission, and PR Transmission will construct, own and operate a new 115 kV transmission line and other associated facilities (the “Interconnection Line” that is defined in Article 1) that will extend from the Project Substation to the Split Rock substation owned by Northern States Power Company (“NSP”) (the point of connection between PR Transmission and NSP being the “Point of Change of Ownership”). C. Prairie Rose directly owns one hundred percent (100%) of the membership interests in PR Transmission. D. Prairie Rose desires, in order to meet its other contractual requirements, to purchase transmission services from PR Transmission for the purpose of delivering two hundred (200) megawatts of electrical energy and capacity from the Project Substation to the Point of Change of Ownership, and PR Transmission desires to provide such transmission services to Prairie Rose on the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement. In consideration of the mutual premises set forth above and the covenants, agreements and provisions made in this Agreement, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, each of the Parties hereto agrees as follows: AGREEMENT 1. Definitions. “Applicable Law” means all laws, constitutions, statutes, rules, regulations, ordinances, judgments, settlements, orders, decrees, injunctions, and writs of any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the Interconnection Line, Prairie Rose, PR Transmission, or the Wind Farm, as applicable. “Business Day” means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, or any federal holiday. “Effective Date” means the effective date granted by FERC in its acceptance of this Agreement. “Emergency” means an imminent event, condition or situation during the Term that (a) with respect to PR Transmission, (i) would constitute an Emergency under the Interconnection Agreement or (ii) in the reasonable judgment of PR Transmission, is likely to (A) endanger life or property or (B) have a material adverse effect on the Wind Farm or the Interconnection Line, and (b) with respect to Prairie Rose, in its reasonable judgment, is likely to (i) endanger life or property or (ii) have a material adverse effect on the Wind Farm or the Interconnection Line. “FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or successor agency. “Governmental Authority” means any governmental department, commission, board, bureau, agency, court or other instrumentality of any country, state, province, county, parish or municipality, jurisdiction, or other political subdivision thereof (including FERC and NERC). “Interconnection Line” means those facilities owned by PR Transmission, including the Project Substation, 115 kV generator interconnection line, and the Pasque Flower Capacitor Station, that are needed to transmit output from the Wind Farm to the Point of Change of Ownership. “Interconnection Agreement” means the Provisional Generator Interconnection Agreement dated October 11, 2011 among Prairie Rose, NSP, and MISO for 200 MW of interconnection service for the Wind Farm, and any other interconnection agreement that may hereafter be entered into in order to interconnect the Wind Farm to the integrated transmission system owned by NSP and controlled by the MISO. “MISO” means the Midwest Independent Transmission System Operator, Inc. “MW” means a unit of power equal to one megawatt. “NERC” means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or any regional entity thereunder (or their respective successors). “NSP” has the meaning given in Recital B. “Option” means NSP’s option to purchase the one hundred megawatt (100 MW) Prairie Rose 2 Wind Project and the Interconnection Line, as provided in that certain Development and Purchase Option Agreement and Separate Option to Purchase Transmission Line dated as of June 30, 2011, by and among Geronimo Wind Energy, LLC, Enel Green Power North America, Inc. and NSP. “Point of Change of Ownership” has the meaning given in Recital B. “Prairie Rose Affiliate” means with respect to Prairie Rose, each such other corporation, partnership or other entity that directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with Prairie Rose. “Project Substation” means that high-voltage substation located adjacent to the Wind Farm Substation and to which the Wind Farm Substation connects. “Proportionate Share” means the ratio of (i) rated nameplate capacity, in MW, of a party’s generating facility to (ii) the aggregate rated nameplate capacities of all generating facilities receiving interconnection and transmission service over the Interconnection Line. “Prudent Utility Practice” means those practices, methods, acts and standards, as changed from time to time, that (i) when engaged in, are commonly used in prudent engineering, contracting and operations to design, construct and operate utility equipment and facilities similar to the Interconnection Line lawfully and with safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy, or (ii) in the exercise of reasonable judgment considering the facts known when engaged in, could have been expected to achieve the desired result consistent with applicable law, safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy. Prudent Utility Practice is not limited to the optimum practices, methods, acts or standards, but includes a spectrum of possible reasonable practices, methods, acts or standards. “Reimbursable Costs” has the meaning given in Section 4(c). “Service Commencement Date” means the first date on which PR Transmission transmits electrical energy from the Wind Farm to the Point of Change of Ownership, which date will occur on the later of (l) the requested service commencement date, or (2) the date on which each of the Interconnection Line and any facilities required under the Interconnection Agreement for MISO to accept delivery from the Wind Farm are energized, or (3) such other date as the interconnection services under this Agreement are permitted to commence by FERC. “Uncontrollable force” has the meaning set forth in Article 13. “Wind Farm” has the meaning given in Recital A. “Wind Farm Substation” means the substation to which the Wind Farm’s collector lines connect. 2. Conditions Precedent to Service Commencing. PR Transmission will have no obligation to deliver the electrical energy from the Wind Farm to the Point of Change of Ownership until the following conditions precedent have been satisfied: (a) The Parties have filed this Agreement with FERC for acceptance under section 205 of the Federal Power Act, and FERC has accepted this Agreement without imposing any condition that either Party considers unacceptable in its reasonable discretion; (b) Prairie Rose has executed the Interconnection Agreement and FERC has accepted the Interconnection Agreement without imposing any condition that Prairie Rose considers unacceptable in its reasonable discretion; and (c) FERC has granted PR Transmission’s request for a waiver from the standards of conduct, and from maintaining an open access transmission tariff and an open access same-time information system. 3. Term. This Agreement will become effective on the Execution Date and will continue in effect for so long as the Interconnection Agreement remains in effect, unless terminated earlier pursuant to this Article 3 or Article 12 or as otherwise mutually agreed in writing by the Parties, plus any time required for disposing of the Interconnection Line as provided in Article 16, provided, that this Agreement will terminate immediately without liability to either Party upon the effective date of a transfer of the Interconnection Line to NSP pursuant to its exercise of the Option. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, this Agreement will not terminate prior to the date designated by FERC as the effective date of termination of this Agreement. 4. Transmission Service. (a) Capacity Reservation. Effective as of the Execution Date, PR Transmission shall reserve two hundred megawatts (200 MW) of firm transfer capability on the Interconnection Line for the purpose of transmitting and delivering up to 200 MW of electrical energy to the Point of Change of Ownership from the Project Substation. (b) Transmission Service. Subject to the conditions precedent in Article 2, beginning at the Service Commencement Date and continuing throughout the remainder of the Term, PR Transmission shall transmit on a firm basis up to 200 MW of electrical energy to the Point of Change of Ownership from the Project Substation. (c) Rate. In accordance with Article 6, Prairie Rose shall pay from time to time all costs, or as applicable its actual out of pocket costs, including any taxes, that PR Transmission reasonably incurs in constructing, owning, operating, and maintaining the Interconnection Line (the “Reimbursable Costs”). For purposes of clarity, any costs for permitting, siting, underlying real property, engineering and design, and equipment procurement reasonably incurred by PR Transmission and associated with the Interconnection Line will be considered Reimbursable Costs that are payable under Section 6(a). Other than payment of the Reimbursable Costs, PR Transmission shall charge Prairie Rose no rate for interconnection or transmission services over the Interconnection Line. PR Transmission shall refund to Prairie Rose any reimbursements from vendors or other third parties, including any insurance payments or any payments collected in connection with resolution of any dispute with such parties, with respect to Reimbursable Costs paid by Prairie Rose to PR Transmission. Prairie Rose shall not be required to pay any costs incurred by PR Transmission for any expansion, modification, repair or upgrade to the Interconnection Line that PR Transmission may make for the purpose of allowing any third party to obtain service using the Interconnection Line. 5. Interconnection Line Construction, Operation and Maintenance. (a) Construction. PR Transmission has the exclusive right and obligation to manage the construction of the Interconnection Line, either directly or through its designee. PR Transmission shall work in good faith to expeditiously complete the Interconnection Line in accordance with the Wind Farm commissioning schedule set forth in the Interconnection Agreement, and shall otherwise construct the Interconnection Line, or cause the Interconnection Line to be constructed, in accordance all applicable laws, including applicable permits and licenses, the Interconnection Agreement, Prudent Utility Practice and all real estate transactions entered into by PR Transmission or Prairie Rose. (b) Operation and Maintenance. During the term of this Agreement, PR Transmission shall exercise Prudent Utility Practice to operate and maintain (or provide for the operation and maintenance of) the Interconnection Line and, in so performing its duties under this Agreement, PR Transmission shall comply with all terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreement and all applicable laws, including applicable permits and licenses. PR Transmission shall provide to Prairie Rose advance written notice of any of its activities that could affect the ability of Prairie Rose to transmit energy on the Interconnection Line (except to the extent that activities must be undertaken in response to an Emergency such that it is not feasible for PR Transmission to provide advance notice) and shall schedule such activities for dates and times that are mutually agreeable, and shall use reasonable efforts consistent with Prudent Utility Practice to conduct such activities in a manner that minimizes any adverse effects on Prairie Rose. (c) Emergencies. Each of the Parties shall promptly notify the other Party of a known Emergency. Notwithstanding any other provision in this Agreement, during an Emergency, PR Transmission has the right to take any action that it reasonably believes is prudent or necessary to (a) preserve public health and safety, (b) limit or prevent damage, (c) preserve the Interconnection Line, or (d) comply with applicable reliability standards, provided that such actions are made in good faith and are consistent with Prudent Utility Practice. Prairie Rose shall reasonably cooperate with, and act in good faith to assist, PR Transmission during an Emergency. PR Transmission shall provide Prairie Rose with prompt notice of any action taken pursuant to this Section 5(c). Neither Party will be liable to the other Party for any action taken pursuant to this Section 5(c). 6. Accounting and Reports; Invoicing and Reimbursement. PR Transmission shall maintain up-to-date books and records of all financial and commercial transactions by PR Transmission with respect to the Interconnection Line. PR Transmission shall maintain such books and records for not less than the period provided by any applicable FERC guidelines or, if longer, two years after delivery of the applicable statement pursuant to Section 6(a). The invoicing and payment of any Reimbursable Costs will be as follows: (a) Not later than ten (10) Business Days after the start of each calendar month (or such other billing period as is agreed by the Parties), PR Transmission shall deliver to Prairie Rose a statement showing the computation in reasonable detail of those Reimbursable Costs that PR Transmission incurred in the prior month, which will include any overpayment or underpayment carried over from previous months. Prairie Rose shall pay to PR Transmission any amount set forth in such statement within ten (10) Business Days. Prairie Rose shall make such payment to PR Transmission in immediately available funds by electronic wire transfer, or by deposit otherwise made into the account designated in writing from time to time by PR Transmission for such purpose. PR Transmission shall promptly provide to Prairie Rose such receipts, documents and other information in connection with each such statement as Prairie Rose may reasonably request to the extent in PR Transmission’s possession or reasonable control. Any dispute concerning a statement will be subject to the dispute resolution process set forth in Article 10. Interest on any unpaid amounts (including amounts placed in escrow) will be calculated in accordance with the methodology specified for interest on refunds in the FERC’s regulations at 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a(a)(2)(iii). Interest on delinquent amounts will be calculated from the due date of the bill to the date of payment. When payments are made by mail, bills will be considered as having been paid on the date of receipt by PR Transmission. (b) Notwithstanding the provisions of Section 6(a) above, PR Transmission shall make available during regular business hours, for inspection and audit by Prairie Rose, all books and records of PR Transmission’s evidencing the amounts for Reimbursable Costs contained in each statement that are attributable to Prairie Rose, including pursuant to Article 7. Prairie Rose shall bear the costs and expenses of any inspection or audit that it requests. Prairie Rose will have the right to conduct such audits with respect to any statement for up to two (2) years following receipt of such statement. (c) PR Transmission also shall permit Prairie Rose to inspect the Interconnection Line during regular business hours, provided that Prairie Rose arranges such inspection with PR Transmission and complies with the safety requirements imposed by PR Transmission. 7. Proportionate Shares. Prior to PR Transmission’s providing interconnection services to any third party over the Interconnection Line, PR Transmission (i) shall establish accounting procedures to segregate all costs and expenses attributable to all parties’ use of the Interconnection Line and (ii) shall reimburse Prairie Rose in an amount equal to (x) all Reimbursable Costs previously paid by Prairie Rose with respect to the Interconnection Line, plus any carrying costs calculated using the FERC rate set forth at 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a, that Prairie Rose has incurred with respect to the Interconnection Line, multiplied by (y) such third party’s Proportionate Share. Prairie Rose shall thereafter reimburse PR Transmission for all Reimbursable Costs according to its Proportionate Share; provided, however, that PR Transmission shall not allocate any costs to Prairie Rose to the extent that PR Transmission has reasonably discerned such costs were caused by the operations or activities of any third-party user(s) of the Interconnection Line. 8. Sole Use Interconnection Line. Prairie Rose and PR Transmission acknowledge and agree that the Interconnection Line is a limited and discrete transmission line that does not comprise an integrated network, and is being constructed for the sole purpose of delivering the output of the Wind Farm from the Project Substation to the Point of Change of Ownership. Prior to providing transmission services to a Prairie Rose Affiliate, PR Transmission shall file a transmission service agreement for acceptance with FERC, and in such filing request that FERC accept the following terms of service as being consistent with FERC precedent and policies; provided, however, that PR Transmission shall have no right to impose such terms of service on any Prairie Rose Affiliate prior to receiving FERC’s acceptance thereof: (a) Any such transmission service agreement filed with FERC by PR Transmission shall include the following provisions: (i) such Prairie Rose Affiliate has no right to, and explicitly waives any right to, service that would at any time or in any way impair, reduce, restrict, interrupt or subordinate Prairie Rose’s rights pursuant to this Agreement; (ii) such Prairie Rose Affiliate shall pay to PR Transmission all costs in accordance with Article 7; (iii) any curtailment or derate will be allocated among Prairie Rose and any Prairie Rose Affiliate with rights to use the Interconnection Line in accordance with each such party’s Proportionate Share, except that any curtailment or derate reasonably determined by PR Transmission, in its sole discretion, to be caused by less than all such parties will be allocated only to the party or parties that caused such curtailment or derate, and any curtailment or derate affecting a portion of the Interconnection Line that is not used by all parties shall be allocated only among the parties using such affected portion; (iv) each such Prairie Rose Affiliate shall cooperate fully with Prairie Rose and PR Transmission in performance of Prairie Rose’s obligations under the Interconnection Agreement; (v) other terms and conditions substantially similar to, or no less favorable to PR Transmission, than the provisions of this Agreement; and (vi) any such Prairie Rose Affiliate shall bear all incremental transmission losses caused by such party’s transmission service using the Interconnection Line. (b) The Parties agree that PR Transmission has no obligation to impose the terms of service in Section 6(a) on any third party that is not a Prairie Rose Affiliate. 9. Insurance. (a) PR Transmission shall procure at the earliest practicable time and thereafter maintain in effect at all times hereinafter the policies of insurance required under the Interconnection Agreement and any additional insurance which PR Transmission in good faith believes is consistent with Prudent Utility Practice for properties and facilities substantially similar to the Interconnection Line. All such policies will contain a waiver of subrogation in favor of Prairie Rose, its officers and employees and shall list Prairie Rose, its officers, employees and agents as an additional insured on a primary/non-contributory basis. If insurance coverage is renewed or replaced during the term of this Agreement, PR Transmission agrees to provide at least thirty (30) days prior to said expiration date, a new certificate of insurance evidencing insurance coverage as provided herein for not less than the remainder of the term of this Agreement, or for a period of not less than one (1) year. PR Transmission shall provide to Prairie Rose a certificate of insurance evidencing all policies of insurance procured by PR Transmission. If any loss, damage or impairment to the Interconnection Line occurs, PR Transmission shall apply the proceeds of any insurance policy with respect thereto to repair, replace or restore the Interconnection Line to its prior condition. (b) Prairie Rose shall procure at the earliest practicable time and thereafter maintain in effect at all times thereafter, insurance which it in good faith believes is consistent with Prudent Utility Practice for properties and facilities substantially similar to the Wind Farm. Prairie Rose shall have the right to self-insure the insurance coverage required to be maintained under this Agreement. Such insurance will include: A. Worker’s Compensation: Statutory Each Occurrence. B. Employer’s Liability: $500,000 Each Person each accident and aggregate. C. General Liability : $2,000,000 per occurrence and aggregate with respect to liability for property damage, bodily injury and death, premises completed operations, contractual liability and products and completed operations. D. Business Auto Policy: $1,000,000.00 Combined Single Limit Automobile Liability, Bodily Injury and Policy to cover all owned if any, non-owned and hired automobile use, including bodily injury and property damage. E. Commercial Umbrella Liability: A minimum of $10,000,000 per occurrence and in the aggregate is required. The policy shall be no less broad than the underlying policy. 10. Dispute Resolution. (a) Each Party shall appoint one (1) person to coordinate with the other Party regarding the performance of this Agreement (each a “Representative” and collectively the “Representatives”). If any dispute arises with respect to either Party’s performance under this Agreement, the Representatives shall meet to attempt to resolve such dispute, either in person or by telephone, within five (5) business days after the written request of either Representative. Except as otherwise provided hereunder, if the Representatives are unable to resolve such dispute, a senior officer of PR Transmission and a senior officer of Prairie Rose shall meet, either in person or by telephone, within ten (10) business days after either Representative provides written notice that the Representatives have been unable to resolve such dispute, to attempt to resolve the dispute. (b) Any disputes arising out of, in connection with or with respect to this Agreement, the subject matter hereof, the performance or non-performance of any obligation hereunder, that cannot be resolved in accordance with Section 10(a), shall be adjudicated in a state or federal court of competent civil jurisdiction sitting in the State of Minnesota. Each of the Parties irrevocably consents and agrees that any legal action or proceedings with respect to this Agreement may be brought in the courts of the State of Minnesota or the United States of America for the District of Minnesota having subject matter jurisdiction and, by execution and delivery of this Agreement and such other documents executed in connection herewith, each Party (i) accepts the exclusive jurisdiction of the aforesaid courts, (ii) irrevocably agrees to be bound by any final judgment (after any and all appeals) of any such court with respect to such documents, (iii) irrevocably waives, to the fullest extent permitted by law, any objection to the laying of venue of any suit, action or proceedings with respect to such documents brought in any such court, and further irrevocably waives, to the fullest extent permitted by law, any claim that any such suit, action or proceedings brought in any such court has been brought in any inconvenient forum, (iv) agrees that service of process in any such action may be effected by mailing a copy thereof by registered or certified mail (or any substantially similar form of mail), postage prepaid, to such Party at its address set forth below, or at such other address of which the other Party hereto has been notified and (v) agrees that nothing herein will affect the right to effect service of process in any other manner permitted by law or limit the right to bring any suit, action or proceeding in any other jurisdiction. (c) EACH OF THE PARTIES KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVES THE RIGHT TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN RESPECT OF ANY LITIGATION BASED HEREON, OR ARISING OUT OF, UNDER OR IN CONNECTION WITH THIS AGREEMENT. THIS PROVISION IS A MATERIAL INDUCEMENT TO EACH OF THE PARTIES FOR ENTERING INTO THIS AGREEMENT. 11. Limitation on Damages. NO PARTY, INCLUDING ANY REPRESENTATIVE, OR ANY SUCH PARTY’S RESPECTIVE MEMBERS, PARTNERS, SUCCESSORS, OR ASSIGNS WILL BE LIABLE (IN CONTRACT OR IN TORT, INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE, STRICT LIABILITY, INDEMNITY, AND WARRANTY) TO THE OTHER PARTY, OR THEIR PARENT CORPORATIONS, AFFILIATES, MEMBERS, PARTNERS, SUCCESSORS, OR ASSIGNS, FOR SPECIAL, INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES IN CONNECTION WITH, ARISING OUT OF OR IN ANY WAY RESULTING FROM SUCH PARTY’S PERFORMANCE, NONPERFORMANCE, OR DELAY IN PERFORMANCE OF ITS OBLIGATIONS UNDER THIS AGREEMENT OR FOR ANY FAILURE OF PERFORMANCE RELATED HERETO, HOWSOEVER CAUSED. 12. Default. (a) In the event Prairie Rose fails, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to PR Transmission on or before the due date as described above in Section 6(a), and such failure of payment is not corrected within ten (10) calendar calendar days after PR Transmission notifies Prairie Rose to cure such failure, a default by the Prairie Rose will be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, PR Transmission may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service under this Agreement but may not terminate service until FERC so approves any such request. In the event of a billing dispute between PR Transmission and Prairie Rose, PR Transmission will continue to provide service under the Agreement as long as Prairie Rose (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute according to the procedures set forth in Article 10. If the Prairie Rose fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then the PR Transmission may provide notice to Prairie Rose of its intention to terminate this Agreement with FERC’s approval. (b) If a Party fails to perform or cause to be performed any obligation (other than a payment obligation) to be performed by it pursuant to the terms, covenants and conditions contained in this Agreement, and such failure is not cured by such Party within thirty (30) days following the date on which such Party is notified of such failure, or, if it is not reasonably practicable to cure such failure within said thirty (30) day period, within a reasonable period following the date on which such Party notice of its failure, such failure will, upon the expiration of the applicable grace period pursuant to this Section 12(b), constitute a default by such Party. (c) The remedies available pursuant to this Article 12 are in addition to and not in lieu of other remedies available to the non-defaulting Party pursuant to this Agreement or at law or in equity, and the exercise of remedies pursuant to this Article 12 does not release the defaulting Party from any of its obligations under this Agreement. In addition to exercising the rights granted in this Article 12, any non-defaulting Party may exercise any right or remedy or take any action available to such non-defaulting Party, at law or in equity, including bringing an action to recover for any loss, damage or payment advances, including reasonable attorneys’ fees, in all trial and appellate courts and collection costs incurred by reason of the default of any Party. (d) Each act or omission to act that constitutes a default under this Agreement will be treated as a separate default under this Article 12. 13. Uncontrollable Forces. No Party will be considered to be in default under this Agreement or in breach of this Agreement on account of any failure in the performance of any of its obligations under this Agreement, other than obligations of such Party to make any payments that are due and owing pursuant to this Agreement, if and to the extent failure of such performance is due to uncontrollable forces. For purposes of this Agreement, the term “uncontrollable forces” means any act of God or any other casualty or occurrence, condition, event or circumstances of any kind or nature not reasonably within the Party’s control (including, without limitation and to the extent otherwise consistent with this definition, acts or omissions of any utility regulatory authority or other governmental authority such as a taking by condemnation or power of eminent domain); requirement of any governmental authority; transmission outages on the integrated transmission grid or sudden or disruptive electrical events or disturbances; strikes; slow downs or labor difficulties (even though such difficulties could be resolved by conceding to the demands of a labor group); fires; flood; earthquakes; explosions; vehicular accidents or other hazards; acts of public enemies; riots; civil commotions; insurrection; and unavailability of supplies or delays in deliveries by suppliers, vendors or subcontractors of any tier, to the extent such suppliers, vendors or subcontractors are subject to an event of the type described in this sentence; provided, however, that neither a Party’s financial inability to perform any payment obligation pursuant to this Agreement nor any change in a Party’s financial condition constitutes an uncontrollable force. Nothing contained herein will be construed so as to require a Party to settle any strike or labor dispute in which it may be involved. Any Party rendered unable to fulfill any obligation under this Agreement by reason of uncontrollable forces shall give written notice of such uncontrollable forces promptly to the other Party and shall exercise due diligence to remove such inability with all reasonable dispatch. 14.Notices. Unless otherwise specifically provided in this Agreement, all notices, demands, requests and other communications required or permitted by the terms of this Agreement to be given to any Party shall be in writing, and any such notice, demand, request or other communication will become effective upon receipt and shall be delivered by certified mail, postage prepaid, for first class mail, or by hand or by facsimile (telecopy), and shall be directed to the address of such Party set forth below: (a) If to PR Transmission, to: c/o Enel Green Power North America, Inc. One Tech Drive, Suite 220 Andover, MA 01810 Attention: Todd Wynn Copy to: Steve Champagne (b) If to Prairie Rose, to: c/o Enel Green Power North America, Inc. One Tech Drive, Suite 220 Andover, MA 01810 Attention: Todd Wynn Copy to: Steve Champagne Either Party may at any time, and from time to time, change its designation of the person to whom notice shall be given by giving notice to the other Party as hereinabove provided. 15. Regulatory Approvals. The Parties shall cooperate in connection with any and all filings and submissions for review, approval, permission or other authorization necessary that may be required from the FERC or by any other entity having the right to review and approve this Agreement. 16. Removal of the Interconnection Line from Service. When Prairie Rose directs PR Transmission to permanently remove the Interconnection Line from service, PR Transmission shall contract to dispose of the Interconnection Line, or of such part of the Interconnection Line, as the case may be, being removed from service; provided, however that Prairie Rose is not entitled to request removal of the Interconnection Line (x) unless Prairie Rose is also permanently decommissioning, and ceasing all operations at, the Wind Farm, (y) if any third party has requested and is entitled to receive future interconnection service or is receiving interconnection services over the Interconnection Line, and (z) until after December 31, 2015. After deducting all reasonable costs of disposing of the Interconnection Line, or of such part or its Proportionate Share of the Interconnection Line, as the case may be, including, without limitation, the reasonable cost of removing all structures and disposing of the debris and meeting all requirements of applicable law, including applicable permits and licenses, PR Transmission shall distribute to Prairie Rose all, or its Proportionate Share, as the case may be, of the net proceeds from such disposition. In the event the reasonable costs of disposing of the Interconnection Line, or of part of the Interconnection Line, as the case may be, pursuant to this Article 15, exceed the amount of the proceeds from the disposition of the Interconnection Line or such part of the Interconnection Line, Prairie Rose shall pay all, or its Proportionate Share, as the case may be, of the excess costs related to the disposition of the Interconnection Line or of such part of the Interconnection Line, as the case may be, as such excess costs are incurred. 17. Representations and Warranties. (a) Organization, Good Standing, Etc. (A) Prairie Rose hereby represents and warrants to PR Transmission as of the Execution Date that Prairie Rose is a limited liability company duly formed, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the State of New York. (B) PR Transmission hereby represents and warrants to Prairie Rose as of the Execution Date that PR Transmission is a limited liability company duly formed, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the State of Minnesota. (b) No Conflicts. (A)The execution, delivery and performance by Prairie Rose of this Agreement does not: (i) violate or conflict with any Applicable Law applicable to or binding on Prairie Rose or, except to the extent provided in Article 2, require any filing with or notice to any Governmental Authority or other entity except for those that (x) have been filed or made or (y) are ministerial in nature and can be reasonably be expected to be filed or made in the ordinary course of business when needed; (ii) conflict with or cause a breach of any provision in the articles of organization, certificate of formation or other organizational document of Prairie Rose; or (iii) cause a breach of, constitute a default under, cause the acceleration of, create in any party the right to accelerate, terminate, modify or cancel, or require any authorization, consent, waiver or approval under any contract, license, instrument, decree, judgment or other arrangement to which Prairie Rose is a party or under which Prairie Rose is bound or to which any of Prairie Rose's assets are subject (or result in the imposition of any encumbrance, upon any such assets). (B) The execution, delivery and performance by PR Transmission of this Agreement does not: (i) violate or conflict with any Applicable Law applicable to or binding on PR Transmission or, except to the extent provided in Article 2, require any filing with or notice to any Governmental Authority or other entity except for those that (x) have been filed or made or (y) are ministerial in nature and can be reasonably be expected to be filed or made in the ordinary course of business when needed; (ii) conflict with or cause a breach of any provision in the articles of organization, certificate of formation or other organizational document of PR Transmission; or (iii) cause a breach of, constitute a default under, cause the acceleration of, create in any party the right to accelerate, terminate, modify or cancel, or require any authorization, consent, waiver or approval under any contract, license, instrument, decree, judgment or other arrangement to which PR Transmission is a party or under which PR Transmission is bound or to which any of PR Transmission's assets are subject (or result in the imposition of any encumbrance, upon any such assets). (c) Authority. (A) Prairie Rose hereby represents and warrants to PR Transmission as of the Execution Date that (i) Prairie Rose has the limited liability company power and authority to enter into this Agreement, and to perform its obligations hereunder, and to consummate the transactions contemplated hereby; (ii) execution and delivery by Prairie Rose of this Agreement has been duly authorized by all necessary limited liability company action required on the part of Prairie Rose; (iii) Prairie Rose has duly executed and delivered this Agreement; and (iv) this Agreement (assuming due authorization, execution and delivery by PR Transmission) constitutes the valid and binding obligations of Prairie Rose enforceable against it in accordance with the terms hereto, subject as to enforceability to applicable bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization, moratorium and similar laws affecting enforcement of creditors’ rights and remedies generally and to general principles of equity (regardless of whether enforcement is sought in a proceeding at law or in equity).
